svg:text.svg:tspan: Glossary
Carboxylic acid
A compound that contains a –COOH functional group.
Catalyst
A substance that increases the rate of a reaction without being
chemically changed or used up in the reaction.
Categoric data
Data that comes in distinct categories, e.g. types of metals etc.
Cathode
An electrode where reduction happens. The negative electrode in electrolysis.
Cation
A particle with a positive charge, formed when one or more electrons are lost.
Ceramic
A non-metallic solid with a high melting point that isn’t
made from carbon-based compounds.
Chemical bond
The attraction of two atoms for each other,
caused by the sharing or transfer of electrons.
Chromatogram
The pattern of spots formed as a result of separating a mixture using chromatography.
Chromatography
A method used to separate the substances in a mixture based on how the
components interact with a mobile phase and a stationary phase.
Climate change
A change in the Earth’s climate. E.g. global warming, changing rainfall patterns etc.
Closed system
A reaction system where no substances can get in or out.
Collision theory
The theory that in order for a reaction to occur,
particles must collide with sufficient energy.
Combustion
An exothermic reaction between a fuel and oxygen.
Complete combustion
Combustion in plenty of oxygen, where the only products are carbon dioxide and water.
Composite
A material made of one or more materials embedded in another.
It will have different properties to the individual compounds.
Compound
A substance made up of atoms of at least two different elements,
chemically joined together.
Concentration
The amount of a substance in a certain volume of solution.
Condensation polymer
A large molecule made from monomers with at least two different functional groups
that react together to form chains. A small molecule is lost for each bond formed.
Conductor
A material that heat or electricity can pass through easily.
Continuous data
Numerical data that can have any value within a range (e.g. length, volume or temperature).
Control variable
A variable in an experiment that is kept the same.
Correlation
A relationship between two variables.
Corrosion
The process of metals being gradually destroyed by
reacting with substances in the environment.
Covalent bond
A chemical bond formed when atoms share a pair of electrons.
Cracking
The process that is used to break long-chain hydrocarbons
down into shorter, moreusefulhydrocarbons.
Crystallisation
The formation of solid crystals as water evaporates from a solution. Forexample,
salt solutions undergo crystallisation to form solid salt crystals.
